THE RISK:
{
 "id": "cra-conformity-clock-outlasts-yam-window",
 "title": "Cyber Resilience Act (Reg. EU 2024/2847): the conformity clock for a networked PDU, started today, ends after the Year-1 window closes",
 "narrative": "An intelligent PDU is a 'product with digital elements' under the CRA. Vulnerability-handling and 24h ENISA incident-reporting obligations apply from 11 September 2026 and full conformity (CE marking against CRA essential requirements, SBOM, coordinated vulnerability disclosure, support-period declaration) from 11 December 2027 — squarely overlapping a pre-launch venture's first 12 months. The harmonized standards CEN/CENELEC must deliver are not yet published, and remote-management functionality risks classifying the product as an 'important product' requiring third-party assessment through a notified-body queue that does not yet exist at scale. Worse, data-center buyers front-run: because PDUs installed in 2026 live in racks past 2027, procurement specs are already demanding CRA-readiness attestations today. The serviceableFactor's 0.55 haircut was built on the old CE/TÜV/ecodesign stack; it prices none of this, and the obtainableFactor's 1% Year-1 pace assumes the product can be quoted into 2026 tenders at all.",
 "category": "exogenous",
 "targetNodes": [
  "serviceableFactor",
  "obtainableFactor"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "CRA obligations land inside the entry window: reporting duties from Sept 2026, full conformity Dec 2027, with harmonized standards unpublished and notified-body capacity unbuilt — a fixed regulatory calendar colliding with a pre-launch stage",
   "refs": [
    "profile:Product",
    "profile:Stage",
    "ledger:serviceableFactor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Large operators and colos, whose gear outlives the 2027 deadline, insert CRA-readiness clauses into 2026 RFQs; the existing cert-stack rationale for serviceableFactor ('justifies <1.0 but doesn't quantify 0.55') already shows the model treats compliance as a static haircut, not a moving gate",
   "refs": [
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c4",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c13",
    "ledger:serviceableFactor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Year-1 tenders that are contestable at all are already scarce and pre-locked 12–24+ months ahead; adding a certification artifact the entrant cannot yet produce removes it from the shortlists that make up the 1% anchor",
   "refs": [
    "digest:refine-demand-discontinuity.prelet-pipeline-lockout#c0",
    "digest:refine-competitive-foreclosure.bundling-eliminates-bakeoffs-year1#c0",
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "Reach shrinks (CRA-gated demand exits the serviceable pool) and pace slows (Year-1 obtainable share falls below the 1% anchor while incumbents ship CRA-ready roadmaps)",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:serviceableFactor",
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "'CE marking' is already a checked box on the founder's compliance list, and the CRA presents itself as just another CE regulation. The trap is procedural, not substantive: the conformity ROUTE changes (SBOM, vulnerability process, possible third-party assessment) and buyers enforce it via procurement one to two years before the legal deadline — so the risk bites in 2026 sales cycles while the founder's calendar says 'deadline 2027'.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "Three 2026 CE data-center PDU RFQs (operator or colo) whose specification documents contain no CRA/cyber-conformity or SBOM requirement, plus confirmation that networked PDUs fall in the CRA default (self-assessment) class.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.5,
  "rationale": "The CRA dates and product scope are enacted law, not forecast; residual uncertainty is only the important-product classification of remote-management PDUs and how aggressively CE buyers front-run the 2027 deadline in 2026 specs. [evidence revision: The regulatory trigger (dates, scope, in-scope status of networked PDUs) is firmly corroborated as enacted law, keeping the core mechanism plausible. But two sub-premises weakened: (1) the 'notified-body queue that does not yet exist' and 'harmonized standards unpublished' argument is softened because Implementing Regulation 2025/2392 (Nov 2025) has fixed technical classifications, and (2) evidence indicates PDUs likely fall in the ~90% default self-assessment class rather than 'important product' third-party assessment — Annex III Class I lists network management systems/routers/switches but not PDUs. The procurement front-running claim ('2026 RFQs demanding CRA-readiness today') is asserted by compliance vendors but not directly evidenced in any actual PDU spec (the Vertiv spec cites only UL/FCC/IEEE, no CRA). Net: strong on the calendar, weaker on the escalation and front-running severity, so slight downward revision from 0.55 to 0.50.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.55
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "serviceableFactor",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.4,
   "note": "CRA-gated (attestation-demanding) demand exits the entrant's reachable pool until conformity artifacts exist"
  },
  {
   "nodeId": "obtainableFactor",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.006,
   "note": "Year-1 pace falls below the 1% anchor as 2026 shortlists require CRA-readiness"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "CRA harmonized-standards progress for network/management devices and the important-product classification of remote-access equipment",
   "where": "CEN/CENELEC JTC 13 work programme and the EU Official Journal harmonized-standards citations; Commission CRA implementing-act docket",
   "threshold": "Networked PDUs / remote management listed under Annex III important products, or harmonized standards slipping past mid-2026",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "CRA/SBOM clauses appearing in data-center electrical RFQs and incumbent price lists",
   "where": "TED (Tenders Electronic Daily) EU data-center fit-out tenders; Schneider/Vertiv/Eaton product-security pages and price-list footnotes announcing CRA-ready SKUs",
   "threshold": "≥2 CE tenders requiring vendor SBOM/CRA attestation, or an incumbent marketing 'CRA-ready' as a differentiator",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Commission a CRA classification and gap assessment (product class, assessment route, notified-body need) with a certified test house now, before design freeze",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "serviceableFactor",
   "note": "Determines whether third-party assessment — the long pole — is required at all"
  },
  {
   "action": "Build the SBOM, secure-development and vulnerability-disclosure artifacts into the launch release and sell them as a differentiator against incumbents' legacy firmware",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Turns the 2026 buyer front-running from a gate into a wedge"
  },
  {
   "action": "Sequence Year-1 pipeline toward buyers not yet writing CRA clauses (mid-market enterprise retrofit) while conformity completes",
   "type": "operational",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": null
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "Cyber Resilience Act (CRA) — DG CONNECT webinar slides",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "ENISA / European Commission DG CONNECT",
   "date": null,
   "excerpt": "Entry into application: 11 December 2027 except for reporting obligations: 11 September 2026. In scope: 'products with digital elements'... network equipment... including their remote data processing solutions!",
   "url": "https://certification.enisa.europa.eu/document/download/9d04238b-7f18-4575-a7dd-638afc92e019_en?filename=Slides_CRA_EUCC_webinar_June_2025.pdf&prefLang=fr",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "CRA Product Classes: Implementing Regulation 2025/2392 Technical Descriptions",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Safeguard",
   "date": "2026-01-15",
   "excerpt": "The default tier — roughly 90 per cent of products — permits self-assessment under conformity assessment Module A... Commission Implementing Regulation (EU) 2025/2392, signed on 28 November 2025... fixes the technical descriptions of each category.",
   "url": "https://safeguard.sh/resources/blog/cra-implementing-regulation-2025-2392-product-classes",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Cyber Resilience Act 2026: A Compliance Guide for OEMs",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "ComponentSense",
   "date": "2026-06-16",
   "excerpt": "From 11th September 2026, electronics manufacturers selling into the EU will be facing a new legal obligation... If your product connects directly or indirectly to a network or device, it falls within scope.",
   "url": "https://www.componentsense.com/blog/cyber-resilience-act-2026-a-compliance-guide-for-oems",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32024R2847",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Regulation (EU) 2024/2847 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 23 October 2024 on horizontal cybersecurity requirements for products with digital elements"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://cloudsmith.com/blog/the-eu-cyber-resilience-act-what-engineering-teams-need-to-do-to-be-compliant",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "On September 11, 2026, vulnerability reporting obligations go live; manufacturers must report actively exploited vulnerabilities to ENISA within 24 hours, even for products already on the market. December 11, 2027, is the full compliance deadline, covering all remaining CRA software requirements, including SBOMs, secure-by-design, CE marking, and technical documentation"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.componentsense.com/blog/cyber-resilience-act-2026-a-compliance-guide-for-oems",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "If your product connects directly or indirectly to a network or device, it falls within scope."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.nlyte.com/blog/smart-vs-dumb-pdus/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Basic PDUs: These are the simplest form of power distribution... From a cybersecurity perspective, their risk is minimal and primarily confined to physical tampering, as they typically have no network connectivity."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://safeguard.sh/resources/blog/cra-implementing-regulation-2025-2392-product-classes",
   "stance": "contradicts",
   "quote": "The default tier — roughly 90 per cent of products — permits self-assessment under conformity assessment Module A."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.craact.eu/regulation/cra/annex/2",
   "stance": "contradicts",
   "quote": "Routers, modems intended for the connection to the internet, and switches"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.vertiv.com/49623f/globalassets/products/critical-power/power-distribution/liebert-tfx-power-distribution-unit/vertiv-liebert-tfx-pdu-guide-specifications-sl-70549.pdf",
   "stance": "silent",
   "quote": "This guide specification describes requirements for a complete power distribution system, supplying computer grade power to sensitive loads."
  }
 ]
}

